full_text: Succeed Insurance has determined that there is a higher incidence of problems with claims from the assigned risk pool. For this reason, Succeed wants to flag all such claims. To accomplish this, I will create a claim pre-setup rule that flags these claims. I'll give the rule a descriptive name. To accomplish this, I will create a claim. The rule will create text, so the best practice is to use a display key. The rules should be triggered by Auto-Claims.  The rules should be triggered by Auto-Claims. Where the policyholder comes from the Assigned-Risk Pool. Assigned-Risk is a Boolean property on policy. The rule must set the claim's flag type key to is underscore flagged. It is also best practice to indicate the reason for the flag. There is an existing display key that will do the job. Now I will save my work. And start the claim center server to test the rule. When the server is fully started, I log on to claim center as Andy Applegate. I'll create a new auto claim. I will make it an unverified policy so I can set the terms myself. I'll give it a policy number that matches Succeed Insurance's standard format. The type of policy is personal auto. I'll set the loss date to today. I'll set the policy number.  Before I set any other terms, I will make this an assigned risk policy. I need to create a policy holder. I'll give the policy holder a name. I'll give the policy number. I'll give the policy an effective date at the beginning of last month. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates.  I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates. I'll give the policy number one of those dates.  So I'll give the policy number one of those dates.     Now I will add a vehicle. I will give the vehicle a make and model and provide a model year. Now I'll add a coverage so there's something for the policy to do. The natural choice for a single coverage is collision. I'll give an exposure limit of $50,000 and the same for the incident limit. Now I'll save the vehicle and proceed with creating the claim. The policyholder is the reporter and their only vehicle is involved. I'll add a quick description of the accident. I'll add a loss cause and select a loss cause that matches the description. I'll provide an address where the accident happened. I'll set the fault rating. And the weather. That's all the required info, so I'll quickly finish out the claim. As Andy Applegate, I'll assign the claim to myself. And I save the claim. If I now view the claim, I see that it is flagged. Hovering over the flag I can see that the reason for the flag is that the policy is assigned risk. This concludes the pre-setup rules demonstration. This concludes the pre-setup rules demonstration.
